		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="107908"></a><b>vaasi_luclin</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails">leaching off society<br />
		<br />
		<br />Joined: 27 Oct 2003<br />Posts: 95</span></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=107908&amp;sid=e98764bf694fbde2207e0f82e5fd7859#107908"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Feb 22, 2005 10:47 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=107908&amp;sid=e98764bf694fbde2207e0f82e5fd7859"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				In 1995, before most people had even heard of the internet, I participated in a videoconference from my employer at the time (Penn State Univ) with a group discussing intellectual property issues of digital media in Washington, DC.  One of the panel members was a representative of the RIAA.
<br />

<br />
Long story short - the RIAA $#&amp;! stated more or less that the "fair use doctrine" as related to education (jurisprudence giving educators the right to present copyrighted materials in classrooms) would be violated if the material shown or played represented "the essence of the material as a whole."  She literally stated that 5 seconds of a 2 hour movie or a 90 minunte CD could be considered the "essence" of it, and that in order to avoid potential infringement suits educators should make a request in writing prior to displaying any copyrighted media (audio, video, or film) in class.
<br />

<br />
That type of stance on intellectual property demonstrates why I have no respect for the RIAA.  Add in the fact that you can buy a new DVD title for about the same price as a 60 minute audio recording, and it comfirms my longstanding suspicion that the RIAA = greed pure and simple.  They are reaping what they've sowed.  Had they followed the film industy's lead on the market tactics (price something low enough to take away incentive to steal it), there'd be a lot more lawyers making a lot less money today.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
