		<td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top">

		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=107911&amp;sid=e98764bf694fbde2207e0f82e5fd7859#107911"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Feb 22, 2005 1:59 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=107911&amp;sid=e98764bf694fbde2207e0f82e5fd7859"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>     </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Those kinds of virus torrents would be easy to identify poppa. Every torrent has a unique ID/hash associated with it, so they'd have to share the ID to get any real propagation done, making it easy to spot and then ignore. Also, how would you get the RIAA to notice it? Users wouldn't propagate those torrents, and no torrent site would list them, so it's unlikely the RIAA would even know they were there.
<br />

<br />
The RIAA is already having enough trouble going after users. They've managed to file lawsuits against something like one thousandth of one percent of the bittorrent users, and take down a handful of high profile sites that are replaced overnight. There can be no legislative solution to a technical problem, as history has proven many times. There is no way for them to win. The courts in some states are even refusing to honor their john doe subpoenas.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> If I legally own the music, say I bought the CD at a local music store. Can I download that CD from the Internet. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
According to the RIAA, no. According to the <span style="font-style: italic">letter</span> of the law, no. According to common sense and simple fair use, hell yes. Take it a step further... you bought Godfather on DVD, and your kids wrecked the disc. Can you download it off of the internet legally? Again, same answers as above. The MPAA would require you to buy the DVD again.
<br />

<br />
This is the crux of the problem. our 'intellectial property' laws make no sense in the digital world. Zero cost copies make the distribution of knowledge and culture so cheap that we may soon need to re-evaluate that as a basic human right. How much would we as a race benefit from connecting everyone to the sum total of human knowledge?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> again it seems as if they track those that share it </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
They tend to target the primary uploaders and sharing sites. Essentially they'll make a target out of any point in the distribution chain that gets big enough to attract their attention. They didn't do this at the outset, but then they ended up suing 12 year old girls and 80 year old grandmothers and ate a truckload of bad press over it. Now they concentrate on distributors since it's unlikely they will find themselves suing someone the public will be so sympathetic over.
<br />

<br />
The price fixing is simply ridiculous.
<br />

<br />
Their days are numbered anyway; I'd say no more than ten years before they are ousted. They've been so busy trying to shut down the distribution channels outside their control (filesharing, dubbing, anything outside of radio/tv/sales essentially) that they don't see the threat to their production monopoly breathing down their necks. It is not going to take much longer before a $5000 PC can outperform a $250,000 recording studio. That liberates musicians from both parts of their monopoly. 
<br />

<br />
They will be able to produce and distribute legally outside of the RIAA's channels, and the same draconian IP laws the RIAA uses now to get their way will be at the disposal of those artists to use against the RIAA when they attempt to do something about it. Those laws benefit the copyright holder, not just the ones with deep pockets, and it's ridiculously easy to sue a corporation or a tradegroup like the RIAA... much easier than it is for them to sue filesharers. The irony is delicious. 
<br />

<br />
Combine that with some form of copyleft public license, and it becomes possible to create a pool of media and culture that is by law forever immune to any proprietary, domineering influences. Any corporations that overstep that line will get smacked with lawsuits from the artists, despite all of it being available to anyone for free as long as they aren't profiting from it directly. This puts the corporations back in the position of <span style="font-style: italic">licensing</span> from the artists, instead of robbing them of their rights.
<br />

<br />
Once public content like that reaches a sort of critical mass (one that free software is fast approaching), it becomes the dominant form of intellectual property in its industry; an open monopoly. This is simply because licensing in copyleft terms is in the best interests of the copyright holder more often than not, because it gives them public recognition and access to the free distribution channels, but leaves them as the sole person who can profit from their work.
<br />

<br />
It solves the filesharing problems, the monopoly problems, the problems of artists getting paid, everything. I can't see any other endpoint to the direction of all the current trends than that. The artists will never repeat the financial success of stars like Bowie, The Beatles, Madonna, etc because they won't be able to sell as much, however they can certainly make a living that way.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
		</table>
		</td>
	</tr>
